# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-backup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-backup/backup] In information technology, a **backup**, or **data backup** is a copy of computer data taken and stored elsewhere so that it may be used to **restore** the original after a data loss event.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The verb form, referring to the process of doing so, is "back up", whereas the noun and adjective form is "backup".
[src:aws-backup/backup] Backups can be used to recover data after its loss from data deletion or corruption, or to recover data from an earlier time.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Backups provide a simple form of IT disaster recovery; however not all backup systems are able to reconstitute a computer system or other complex configuration such as a computer cluster, active directory server, or database server.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A backup system contains at least one copy of all data considered worth saving.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The data storage requirements can be large.
[src:aws-backup/backup] An information repository model may be used to provide structure to this storage.
[src:aws-backup/backup] There are different types of data storage devices used for copying backups of data that is already in secondary storage onto archive files.
[src:aws-backup/backup] There are also different ways these devices can be arranged to provide geographic dispersion, data security, and portability.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Data is selected, extracted, and manipulated for storage.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The process can include methods for dealing with live data, including open files, as well as compression, encryption, and de-duplication.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Additional techniques apply to enterprise client-server backup.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Backup schemes may include dry runs that validate the reliability of the data being backed up.
[src:aws-backup/backup] There are limitations and human factors involved in any backup scheme.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A backup strategy requires an information repository, "a secondary storage space for data" that aggregates backups of data "sources".
[src:aws-backup/backup] The repository could be as simple as a list of all backup media (DVDs, etc.) and the dates produced, or could include a computerized index, catalog, or relational database.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The backup data needs to be stored, requiring a backup rotation scheme, which is a system of backing up data to computer media that limits the number of backups of different dates retained separately, by appropriate re-use of the data storage media by overwriting of backups no longer needed.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The scheme determines how and when each piece of removable storage is used for a backup operation and how long it is retained once it has backup data stored on it.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The 3-2-1 rule can aid in the backup process.
[src:aws-backup/backup] It states that there should be at least 3 copies of the data, stored on 2 different types of storage media, and one copy should be kept offsite, in a remote location (this can include cloud storage).
[src:aws-backup/backup] 2 or more different media should be used to eliminate data loss due to similar reasons (for example, optical discs may tolerate being underwater while LTO tapes may not, and SSDs cannot fail due to head crashes or damaged spindle motors since they do not have any moving parts, unlike hard drives).
[src:aws-backup/backup] An offsite copy protects against fire, theft of physical media (such as tapes or discs) and natural disasters like floods and earthquakes.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Physically protected hard drives are an alternative to an offsite copy, but they have limitations like only being able to resist fire for a limited period of time, so an offsite copy still remains as the ideal choice.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Because there is no perfect storage, many backup experts recommend maintaining a second copy on a local physical device, even if the data is also backed up offsite.
[src:aws-backup/backup] An unstructured repository may simply be a stack of tapes, DVD-Rs or external HDDs with minimal information about what was backed up and when.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This method is the easiest to implement, but unlikely to achieve a high level of recoverability as it lacks automation.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A repository using this backup method contains complete source data copies taken at one or more specific points in time.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Copying system images, this method is frequently used by computer technicians to record known good configurations.
[src:aws-backup/backup] However, imaging is generally more useful as a way of deploying a standard configuration to many systems rather than as a tool for making ongoing backups of diverse systems.
[src:aws-backup/backup] An incremental backup stores data changed since a reference point in time.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Duplicate copies of unchanged data are not copied.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Typically a full backup of all files is made once or at infrequent intervals, serving as the reference point for an incremental repository.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Subsequently, a number of incremental backups are made after successive time periods.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Restores begin with the last full backup and then apply the incrementals.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Some backup systems can create a synthetic full backup from a series of incrementals, thus providing the equivalent of frequently doing a full backup.
[src:aws-backup/backup] When done to modify a single archive file, this speeds restores of recent versions of files.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Continuous Data Protection (CDP) refers to a backup that instantly saves a copy of every change made to the data.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This allows restoration of data to any point in time and is the most comprehensive and advanced data protection.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Near-CDP backup applications—often marketed as "CDP"—automatically take incremental backups at a specific interval, for example every 15 minutes, one hour, or 24 hours.
[src:aws-backup/backup] They can therefore only allow restores to an interval boundary.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Near-CDP backup applications use journaling and are typically based on periodic "snapshots", read-only copies of the data frozen at a particular point in time.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Near-CDP (except for Apple Time Machine) intent-logs every change on the host system, often by saving byte or block-level differences rather than file-level differences.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This backup method differs from simple disk mirroring in that it enables a roll-back of the log and thus a restoration of old images of data.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Near-CDP is more practicable for ordinary personal backup applications, as opposed to *true* CDP, which must be run in conjunction with a virtual machine or equivalent and is therefore generally used in enterprise client-server backups.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Software may create copies of individual files such as written documents, multimedia projects, or user preferences, to prevent failed write events caused by power outages, operating system crashes, or exhausted disk space, from causing data loss.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A common implementation is an appended ".bak" extension to the file name.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A Reverse incremental backup method stores a recent archive file "mirror" of the source data and a series of differences between the "mirror" in its current state and its previous states.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A reverse incremental backup method starts with a non-image full backup.
[src:aws-backup/backup] After the full backup is performed, the system periodically synchronizes the full backup with the live copy, while storing the data necessary to reconstruct older versions.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This can either be done using hard links—as Apple Time Machine does, or using binary diffs.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A differential backup saves only the data that has changed since the last full backup.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This means a maximum of two backups from the repository are used to restore the data.
[src:aws-backup/backup] However, as time from the last full backup (and thus the accumulated changes in data) increases, so does the time to perform the differential backup.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Restoring an entire system requires starting from the most recent full backup and then applying just the last differential backup.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Changes in files may be detected through a more recent date/time of last modification file attribute, and/or changes in file size.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Other variations of incremental backup include multi-level incrementals and block-level incrementals that compare parts of files instead of just entire files.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Regardless of the repository model that is used, the data has to be copied onto an archive file data storage medium.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The medium used is also referred to as the type of backup destination.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Magnetic tape was for a long time the most commonly used medium for bulk data storage, backup, archiving, and interchange.
[src:aws-backup/backup] It was previously a less expensive option, but this is no longer the case for smaller amounts of data.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Tape is a sequential access medium, so the rate of continuously writing or reading data can be very fast.
[src:aws-backup/backup] While tape media itself has a low cost per space, tape drives are typically dozens of times as expensive as hard disk drives and optical drives.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Tape media are generally rotated on a schedule so at least one set is off-site in case something should happen to the building where the primary copy of the data lives.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Many tape formats have been proprietary or specific to certain markets like mainframes or a particular brand of personal computer.
[src:aws-backup/backup] By 2014 LTO had become the primary tape technology.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The other remaining viable "super" format is the IBM 3592 (also referred to as the TS11xx series).
[src:aws-backup/backup] The Oracle StorageTek T10000 was discontinued in 2016.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The use of hard disk storage has increased over time as it has become progressively cheaper.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Hard disks are usually easy to use, widely available, and can be accessed quickly.
[src:aws-backup/backup] However, hard disk backups are close-tolerance mechanical devices and may be more easily damaged than tapes, especially while being transported.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Some manufacturers also offer 'ruggedized' portable hard drives, which include a shock-absorbing case around the hard disk, and claim a range of higher drop specifications.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Over a period of years the stability of hard disk backups is shorter than that of tape backups.
[src:aws-backup/backup] External hard disks can be connected via local interfaces like SCSI, USB, FireWire, or eSATA, or via longer-distance technologies like Ethernet, iSCSI, or Fibre Channel.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Some disk-based backup systems, via Virtual Tape Libraries or otherwise, support data deduplication, which can reduce the amount of disk storage capacity consumed by daily and weekly backup data.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Optical storage uses lasers to store and retrieve data.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Recordable CDs, DVDs, and Blu-ray Discs are commonly used with personal computers and are generally cheap.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The capacities and speeds of these discs have typically been lower than hard disks or tapes.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Advances in optical media may shrink that gap in the future.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Potential future data losses caused by gradual media degradation can be predicted by measuring the rate of correctable minor data errors, of which consecutively too many increase the risk of uncorrectable sectors.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Support for error scanning varies among optical drive vendors.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Many optical disc formats are WORM type, which makes them useful for archival purposes since the data cannot be changed in any way, including by user error and by malware such as ransomware.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Moreover, optical discs are not vulnerable to head crashes, magnetism, imminent water ingress or power surges; and, a fault of the drive typically just halts the spinning.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Optical media is modular; the storage controller is not tied to media itself like with hard drives or flash storage (→flash memory controller), allowing it to be removed and accessed through a different drive.
[src:aws-backup/backup] However, recordable media may degrade earlier under long-term exposure to light.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Some optical storage systems allow for cataloged data backups without human contact with the discs, allowing for longer data integrity.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A French study in 2008 indicated that the lifespan of typically-sold CD-Rs was 2–10 years, but one manufacturer later estimated the longevity of its CD-Rs with a gold-sputtered layer to be as high as 100 years.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Sony's proprietary Optical Disc Archive can in 2016 reach a read rate of 250 MB/s.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Solid-state drives (SSDs) use integrated circuit assemblies to store data.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Flash memory, thumb drives, USB flash drives, CompactFlash, SmartMedia, Memory Sticks, and Secure Digital card devices are relatively expensive for their low capacity, but convenient for backing up relatively low data volumes.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A solid-state drive does not contain any movable parts, making it less susceptible to physical damage, and can have huge throughput of around 500 Mbit/s up to 6 Gbit/s.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Available SSDs have become more capacious and cheaper.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Flash memory backups are stable for fewer years than hard disk backups.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Remote backup services or cloud backups involve service providers storing data offsite.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This has been used to protect against events such as fires, floods, or earthquakes which could destroy locally stored backups.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Cloud-based backup (through services like or similar to Google Drive, and Microsoft OneDrive) provides a layer of data protection.
[src:aws-backup/backup] However, the users must trust the provider to maintain the privacy and integrity of their data, with confidentiality enhanced by the use of encryption.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Because speed and availability are limited by a user's online connection, users with large amounts of data may need to use seed loading and bulk restore.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Various methods can be used to manage backup media, striking a balance between accessibility, security and cost.
[src:aws-backup/backup] These media management methods are not mutually exclusive and are frequently combined to meet the user's needs.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Using on-line disks for staging data before it is sent to a near-line tape library is a common example.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Online backup storage is typically the most accessible type of data storage, and can begin a restore in milliseconds.
[src:aws-backup/backup] An internal hard disk or a disk array (maybe connected to SAN) is an example of an online backup.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This type of storage is convenient and speedy, but is vulnerable to being deleted or overwritten, either by accident, by malevolent action, or in the wake of a data-deleting virus payload.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Nearline storage is typically less accessible and less expensive than online storage, but still useful for backup data storage.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A mechanical device is usually used to move media units from storage into a drive where the data can be read or written.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Generally it has safety properties similar to on-line storage.
[src:aws-backup/backup] An example is a tape library with restore times ranging from seconds to a few minutes.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Off-line storage requires some direct action to provide access to the storage media: for example, inserting a tape into a tape drive or plugging in a cable.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Because the data is not accessible via any computer except during limited periods in which they are written or read back, they are largely immune to on-line backup failure modes.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Access time varies depending on whether the media are on-site or off-site.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Backup media may be sent to an off-site vault to protect against a disaster or other site-specific problem.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The vault can be as simple as a system administrator's home office or as sophisticated as a disaster-hardened, temperature-controlled, high-security bunker with facilities for backup media storage.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A data replica can be off-site but also on-line (e.g., an off-site RAID mirror).
[src:aws-backup/backup] A backup site or disaster recovery center is used to store data that can enable computer systems and networks to be restored and properly configured in the event of a disaster.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Some organisations have their own data recovery centres, while others contract this out to a third-party.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Due to high costs, backing up is rarely considered the preferred method of moving data to a DR site.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A more typical way would be remote disk mirroring, which keeps the DR data as up to date as possible.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A backup operation starts with selecting and extracting coherent units of data.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Most data on modern computer systems is stored in discrete units, known as files.
[src:aws-backup/backup] These files are organized into filesystems.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Deciding what to back up at any given time involves tradeoffs.
[src:aws-backup/backup] By backing up too much redundant data, the information repository will fill up too quickly.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Backing up an insufficient amount of data can eventually lead to the loss of critical information.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Files that are actively being updated present a challenge to back up.
[src:aws-backup/backup] One way to back up live data is to temporarily quiesce them (e.g., close all files), take a "snapshot", and then resume live operations.
[src:aws-backup/backup] At this point the snapshot can be backed up through normal methods.
[src:aws-backup/backup] A snapshot is an instantaneous function of some filesystems that presents a copy of the filesystem as if it were frozen at a specific point in time, often by a copy-on-write mechanism.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Snapshotting a file while it is being changed results in a corrupted file that is unusable.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This is also the case across interrelated files, as may be found in a conventional database or in applications such as Microsoft Exchange Server.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The term fuzzy backup can be used to describe a backup of live data that looks like it ran correctly, but does not represent the state of the data at a single point in time.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Not all information stored on the computer is stored in files.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Accurately recovering a complete system from scratch requires keeping track of this non-file data too.
[src:aws-backup/backup] It is frequently useful or required to manipulate the data being backed up to optimize the backup process.
[src:aws-backup/backup] These manipulations can improve backup speed, restore speed, data security, media usage and/or reduced bandwidth requirements.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Out-of-date data can be automatically deleted, but for personal backup applications—as opposed to enterprise client-server backup applications where automated data "grooming" can be customized—the deletion can at most be globally delayed or be disabled.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Various schemes can be employed to shrink the size of the source data to be stored so that it uses less storage space.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Compression is frequently a built-in feature of tape drive hardware.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Redundancy due to backing up similarly configured workstations can be reduced, thus storing just one copy.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This technique can be applied at the file or raw block level.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This potentially large reduction is called deduplication.
[src:aws-backup/backup] It can occur on a server before any data moves to backup media, sometimes referred to as source/client side deduplication.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This approach also reduces bandwidth required to send backup data to its target media.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The process can also occur at the target storage device, sometimes referred to as inline or back-end deduplication.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Sometimes backups are duplicated to a second set of storage media.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This can be done to rearrange the archive files to optimize restore speed, or to have a second copy at a different location or on a different storage medium—as in the disk-to-disk-to-tape capability of Enterprise client-server backup.
[src:aws-backup/backup] High-capacity removable storage media such as backup tapes present a data security risk if they are lost or stolen.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Encrypting the data on these media can mitigate this problem, however encryption is a CPU intensive process that can slow down backup speeds, and the security of the encrypted backups is only as effective as the security of the key management policy.
[src:aws-backup/backup] When there are many more computers to be backed up than there are destination storage devices, the ability to use a single storage device with several simultaneous backups can be useful.
[src:aws-backup/backup] However cramming the scheduled backup window via "multiplexed backup" is only used for tape destinations.
[src:aws-backup/backup] The process of rearranging the sets of backups in an archive file is known as refactoring.
[src:aws-backup/backup] For example, if a backup system uses a single tape each day to store the incremental backups for all the protected computers, restoring one of the computers could require many tapes.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Refactoring could be used to consolidate all the backups for a single computer onto a single tape, creating a "synthetic full backup".
[src:aws-backup/backup] This is especially useful for backup systems that do incrementals forever style backups.
[src:aws-backup/backup] Sometimes backups are copied to a staging disk before being copied to tape.
[src:aws-backup/backup] This process is sometimes referred to as D2D2T, an acronym for Disk-to-disk-to-tape.
[src:aws-backup/backup] It can be useful if there is a problem matching the speed of the final destination device with the source device, as is frequently faced in network-based backup systems.
[src:aws-backup/backup] It can also serve as a centralized location for applying other data manipulation techniques.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] The concept of data management emerged alongside the evolution of computing technology.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] In the 1950s, as computers became more prevalent, organizations began to grapple with the challenge of organizing and storing data efficiently.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Early methods relied on punch cards and manual sorting, which were labor-intensive and prone to errors.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] The introduction of database management systems in the 1970s marked a significant milestone, enabling structured storage and retrieval of data.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] By the 1980s, relational database models revolutionized data management, emphasizing the importance of data as an asset and fostering a data-centric mindset in business.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] This era also saw the rise of data governance practices, which prioritized the organization and regulation of data to ensure quality and compliance.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Over time, advancements in technology, such as cloud computing and big data analytics, have further refined data management, making it a cornerstone of modern business operations.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] As of 2025, data management encompasses a wide range of practices, from data storage and security to analytics and decision-making, reflecting its critical role in driving innovation and efficiency across industries.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] The Data Management Body of Knowledge, DMBoK, developed by the Data Management Association, DAMA, outlines key knowledge areas that serve as the foundation for modern data management practices, suggesting a framework for organizations to manage data as a strategic asset.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data governance refers to the policies, procedures, and standards that ensure data is managed consistently and responsibly across an organization.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] In enterprise contexts, governance involves aligning stakeholders across business units, defining data ownership, and quantifying the benefits of improved data quality.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Effective governance frameworks often include data stewardship roles, escalation protocols, and cross-functional oversight committees to maintain trust and accountability in data use.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data architecture consist of models, policies, rules, and standards that govern which data is collected and how it is stored, arranged, integrated, and put to use in data systems and in organizations.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data Architecture focuses on designing the overall structure of data systems.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It ensures that data flows are efficient and that systems are scalable, adaptable, and aligned with business needs.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] This area centers on creating models that logically represent data relationships.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It’s essential for both designing databases and ensuring that data is structured in a way that facilitates analysis and reporting.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Deals with the physical storage of data and its day-to-day management.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] This includes everything from traditional data centers to cloud-based storage solutions and ensuring efficient data processing.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Ensures that data from various sources can be seamlessly shared and combined across multiple systems, which is critical for comprehensive analytics and decision-making.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Focuses on managing unstructured data such as documents, multimedia, and other content, ensuring that it is stored, categorized, and easily retrievable.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Involves consolidating data into repositories that support analytics, reporting, and business insights.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] In computing, a data warehouse (DW or DWH), also known as an enterprise data warehouse (EDW), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Business intelligence (BI) consists of strategies, methodologies, and technologies used by enterprises for data analysis and management of business information to inform business strategies and business operations.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Common functions of BI technologies include reporting, online analytical processing, analytics, dashboard development, data mining, process mining, complex event processing, business performance management, benchmarking, text mining, predictive analytics, and prescriptive analytics.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] A data mart is a structure/access pattern specific to *data warehouse* environments.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] The data mart is a subset of the data warehouse that focuses on a specific business line, department, subject area, or team.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Whereas data warehouses have an enterprise-wide depth, the information in data marts pertains to a single department.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] In some deployments, each department or business unit is considered the *owner* of its data mart, including all the *hardware*, *software*, and *data*.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] This enables each department to isolate the use, manipulation, and development of their data.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] In other deployments where conformed dimensions are used, this business unit ownership will not hold true for shared dimensions like customer, product, etc.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data analysis is the process of inspecting, cleansing, transforming, and modeling data with the goal of discovering useful information, informing conclusions, and supporting decision-making.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data analysis has multiple facets and approaches, encompassing diverse techniques under a variety of names, and is used in different business, science, and social science domains.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] In today's business world, data analysis plays an important role in making decisions more scientific and helping businesses operate more effectively.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It is widely used in fields such as business analytics, healthcare, and artificial intelligence to extract meaningful insights from data.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data mining is the process of extracting and finding patterns in massive data sets involving methods at the intersection of machine learning, statistics, and database systems.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data mining is an interdisciplinary subfield of computer science and statistics with an overall goal of extracting information (with intelligent methods) from a data set and transforming the information into a comprehensible structure for further use.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data mining is the analysis step of the "knowledge discovery in databases" process, or KDD.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Aside from the raw analysis step, it also involves database and data management aspects, data pre-processing, model and inference considerations, interestingness metrics, complexity considerations, post-processing of discovered structures, visualization, and online updating.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] A data scientist is a professional who creates programming code and combines it with statistical knowledge to summarize data.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Manages data about data, including definitions, origin, and usage, to enhance the understanding and usability of the organization’s data assets.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data quality is not only a technical concern but a strategic enabler of trust, compliance, and decision-making.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] High-quality data supports consistent reporting, regulatory adherence, and customer confidence.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Enterprise data management programs often define quality metrics such as precision, granularity, and timeliness, and link these to business outcomes.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Reference data comprises standardized codes and values for consistent interpretation across systems.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Master data management (MDM) governs and centralizes an organization’s critical data, ensuring a unified, reliable information source that supports effective decision-making and operational efficiency.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data security refers to a comprehensive set of practices and technologies designed to protect digital information and systems from unauthorized access, use, disclosure, modification, or destruction.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It encompasses encryption, access controls, monitoring, and risk assessments to maintain data integrity, confidentiality, and availability.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Data privacy involves safeguarding individuals’ personal information by ensuring its collection, storage, and use comply with consent, legal standards, and confidentiality principles.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It emphasizes protecting sensitive data from misuse or unauthorized access while respecting users' rights.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] The distinction between data and derived value is illustrated by the "information ladder" or the DIKAR model.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] The "DIKAR" model stands for Data, Information, Knowledge, Action, and Result.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It is a framework used to bridge the gap between raw data and actionable outcomes.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] The model emphasizes the transformation of data into information, which is then interpreted to create knowledge.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] This knowledge guides actions that lead to measurable results.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] DIKAR is widely applied in organizational strategies, helping businesses align their data management processes with decision-making and performance goals.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] By focusing on each stage, the model ensures that data is effectively utilized to drive informed decisions and achieve desired outcomes.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It is particularly valuable in technology-driven environments.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] The "information ladder" illustrates the progression from data (raw facts) to information (processed data), knowledge (interpreted information), and ultimately wisdom (applied knowledge).
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Each step adds value and context, enabling better decision-making.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It emphasizes the transformation of unstructured inputs into meaningful insights for practical use.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] In research, Data management refers to the systematic process of handling data throughout its lifecycle.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] This includes activities such as collecting, organizing, storing, analyzing, and sharing data to ensure its accuracy, accessibility, and security.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] A Data Management Plan (DMP) is a structured document that outlines how research data will be collected, organized, stored, shared, and preserved throughout and after a research project.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It serves as a guide to ensure that data are handled responsibly, remain accessible, and are protected from loss or misuse.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Effective data management also involves creating a data management plan, DMP, addressing issues like ethical considerations, compliance with regulatory standards, and long-term preservation.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Proper management enhances research transparency, reproducibility, and the efficient use of resources, ultimately contributing to the credibility and impact of research findings.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] It is a critical practice across disciplines to ensure data integrity and usability both during and after a research project.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Big data refers to the collection and analyses of massive sets of data.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] While big data is a recent phenomenon, the requirement for data to aid decision-making traces back to the early 1970s with the emergence of decision support systems (DSS).
[src:aws-backup/data-management] These systems can be considered as the initial iteration of data management for decision support.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Studies indicate that customer transactions account for a 40% increase in the data collected annually, which means that financial data has a considerable impact on business decisions.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Therefore, modern organizations are using big data analytics to identify 5 to 10 new data sources that can help them collect and analyze data for improved decision-making.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Jonsen (2013) explains that organizations using average analytics technologies are 20% more likely to gain higher returns compared to their competitors who have not introduced any analytics capabilities in their operations.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Also, IRI reported that the retail industry could experience an increase of more than $10 billion each year resulting from the implementation of modern analytics technologies.
[src:aws-backup/data-management] Therefore, the following hypothesis can be proposed: Economic and financial outcomes can impact how organizations use data analytics tools.
[src:aws-backup/point-in-time-recovery] Once PITR logging starts for a PITR-capable database, a database administrator can restore that database from backups to the state that it had at any time since.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:aws-backup/replication-computing] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] In computer systems, a **snapshot** is the state of a system at a particular point in time.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] The term was coined as an analogy to that in photography.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] A full backup of a large data set may take a long time to complete.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] On multi-tasking or multi-user systems, there may be writes to that data while it is being backed up.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] This prevents the backup from being atomic and introduces a version skew that may result in data corruption.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] For example, if a user moves a file into a directory that has already been backed up, then that file would be completely missing on the backup media, since the backup operation had already taken place before the addition of the file.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Version skew may also cause corruption with files which change their size or contents underfoot while being read.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] One approach to safely backing up live data is to temporarily disable write access to data during the backup, either by stopping the accessing applications or by using the locking API provided by the operating system to enforce exclusive read access.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] This is tolerable for low-availability systems (on desktop computers and small workgroup servers, on which regular downtime is acceptable).
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] High-availability 24/7 systems, however, cannot bear service stoppages.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] To avoid downtime, high-availability systems may instead perform the backup on a *snapshot*—a read-only copy of the data set frozen at a point in time—and allow applications to continue writing to their data.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Most snapshot implementations are efficient and can create snapshots in *O(1)*.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] In other words, the time and I/O needed to create the snapshot does not increase with the size of the data set; by contrast, the time and I/O required for a direct backup is proportional to the size of the data set.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] In some systems once the initial snapshot is taken of a data set, subsequent snapshots copy the changed data only, and use a system of pointers to reference the initial snapshot.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] This method of pointer-based snapshots consumes less disk capacity than if the data set was repeatedly cloned.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Some Unix systems have snapshot-capable logical volume managers.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] These implement copy-on-write on entire block devices by copying changed blocks‍—‌just before they are to be overwritten within "parent" volumes‍—‌to other storage, thus preserving a self-consistent past image of the block device.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Filesystems on such snapshot images can later be mounted as if they were on a read-only media.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Some volume managers also allow creation of *writable* snapshots, extending the copy-on-write approach by disassociating any blocks modified within the snapshot from their "parent" blocks in the original volume.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Such a scheme could be also described as performing additional copy-on-write operations triggered by the writes to snapshots.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] On Linux, Logical Volume Manager (LVM) allows creation of both read-only and read-write snapshots.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Writable snapshots were introduced with the LVM version 2 (LVM2).
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Some file systems, such as WAFL, fossil for Plan 9 from Bell Labs, and ODS-5, internally track old versions of files and make snapshots available through a special namespace.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Others, like UFS2, provide an operating system API for accessing file histories.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] In NTFS, access to snapshots is provided by the Volume Shadow-copying Service (VSS) in Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 and Shadow Copy in Windows Vista.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Melio FS provides snapshots via the same VSS interface for shared storage.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Snapshots have also been available in the NSS (Novell Storage Services) file system on NetWare since version 4.11, and more recently on Linux platforms in the Open Enterprise Server product.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] EMC's Isilon OneFS clustered storage platform implements a single scalable file system that supports read-only snapshots at the file or directory level.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Any file or directory within the file system can be snapshotted and the system will implement a copy-on-write or point-in-time snapshot dynamically based on which method is determined to be optimal for the system.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] On Linux, the Btrfs and OCFS2 file systems support creating snapshots (cloning) of individual files.
[src:aws-backup/snapshot-computer-storage] Additionally, Btrfs also supports the creation of snapshots of subvolumes.
